<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="60" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="60">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="60">
The species was previously synonymised under 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. tweedieanum" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" rank="species" species="tweedieanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="60">P. tweedieanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. tweedieanum" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" rank="species" species="tweedieanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="60">T. tweedieanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) by 
<bibRefCitation author="Croat, TB" editor="Bocquet, GF" journalOrPublisher="Conservatoire et Jardin Botaniques de la Ville de Geneve and Missouri Botanical Garden, Geneva and St. Louis (11)" pageId="13" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 47" refId="B8" refString="Croat, TB, Mount, D, 1988. Araceae. In: Bocquet, GF, Crosby, MR, Eds., Flora del Paraguay. Conservatoire et Jardin Botaniques de la Ville de Geneve and Missouri Botanical Garden, Geneva and St. Louis (11): 1 - 47" title="Araceae." volumeTitle="Flora del Paraguay." year="1988">Croat and Mount (1988)</bibRefCitation>
. We propose its reinstatement as an accepted species based on the following morphological differences: herbs erect and rupiculous (x herbs decumbent or rhizomatous subterranean acaulous in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. tweedieanum" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" rank="species" species="tweedieanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="60">T. tweedieanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), prophyll deciduous when still herbaceous (x marcescent and persistent-membranous in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. tweedieanum" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" rank="species" species="tweedieanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="60">T. tweedieanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), denudation of posterior division absent (x present in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. tweedieanum" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" rank="species" species="tweedieanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="60">T. tweedieanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), presence of stylar central dome in pistillate flowers (x absence of stylar central dome in 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. tweedieanum" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" rank="species" species="tweedieanum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="60">T. tweedieanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Besides having a different gynoecium type (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.flora.2013.12.004" author="Calazans, LSB" journalOrPublisher="Flora (Jena)" pageId="13" pageNumber="64" pagination="117 - 121" refId="B6" refString="Calazans, LSB, Sakuragui, CM, Mayo, SJ, 2014. From open areas to forest? The evolutionary history of Philodendron subgenus Meconostigma using morphological data. Flora (Jena) 209 (2): 117 - 121, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.flora.2013.12.004" title="From open areas to forest? The evolutionary history of Philodendron subgenus Meconostigma using morphological data." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.flora.2013.12.004" volume="209" year="2014">Calazans et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
), the majority-rule consensus tree based on morphological characters support these species as different lineages. Furthermore, the phylogeny based on molecular characters supports the two species as separate taxa (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0089701" author="Loss-Oliveira, L" journalOrPublisher="Molecular Biology and Evolution" pageId="14" pageNumber="65" refId="B20" refString="Loss-Oliveira, L, Calazans, LSB, Morais, EB, Mayo, SJ, Schrago, CEG, Sakuragui, CM, 2014. Floral evolution of Philodendron subgenus Meconostigma (Araceae). PLoS One 9(2): e89701. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0089701" title="Floral evolution of Philodendron subgenus Meconostigma (Araceae). PLoS One 9 (2): e 89701." url="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0089701" year="2014">Loss-Oliveira et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Schott" authorityName="Sakur., Calazans &amp; Mayo" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Sakuragui &amp; Calazans &amp; Oliveira &amp; Morais &amp; Benko-Iseppon &amp; Vasconcelos &amp; Schrago &amp; Mayo" baseAuthorityYear="2018" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Thaumatophyllum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Thaumatophyllum petraeum" order="Alismatales" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="petraeum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="60">Thaumatophyllum petraeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was first described for Paraguay with four varieties and are still recorded only from this country. We have no evidence to recognise the varieties as distinct taxa, except for. 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. petraeum subsp. var. var. tobatiense" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" rank="variety" species="petraeum" subSpecies="var." variety="tobatiense">P. petraeum var. tobatiense</taxonomicName>
Chodat &amp; Vischer, which is a synonymous of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. undulatum" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" rank="species" species="undulatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="60">P. undulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(= 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. undulatum" pageId="9" pageNumber="60" rank="species" species="undulatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="60">T. undulatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
